 1 file changed, 55 insertions(+)

diff --git a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
index 4f67364f3..9d3bc2e7f 100644
--- a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -249,3 +249,58 @@
 
 ---
 
+---
+
+## Why CVE-2025-66864 Is a False Positive for **binutils 2.40** on Debian Bookworm
+
+---
+
+## 📌 CVE-2025-66864 – False Positive in binutils 2.40
+
+**Component:** `d_print_comp_inner` in `libiberty/cp-demangle.c` (C++ demangler)
+**Issue:** NULL pointer dereference when processing crafted PE file input via `cxxfilt`
+**Impact:** Denial of service (crash) when running demangler tools on crafted binaries in binutils **2.26** only
+
+---
+
+## 🔍 Vulnerability Overview
+
+- **Component impacted:** GNU libiberty (`cp-demangle.c` — `d_print_comp_inner`)
+- **Nature of issue:** `d_right()` returns NULL for crafted input; in binutils 2.26, the result is passed directly into `while (local_name->type == ...)` without a NULL check, causing SIGSEGV
+- **Severity:** Low (CVSS 3.1: 3.3 per Red Hat; 5.5 per NVD)
+- **Attack vector:** Local — processing crafted binary with `cxxfilt` or `nm -C`
+- **CVE filed against:** binutils **2.26** (released January 2016)
+
+---
+
+## ✅ binutils 2.40 – Why This is a False Positive
+
+- **The vulnerable code no longer exists in 2.40** — the crash path was eliminated through organic refactoring of the `DEMANGLE_COMPONENT_TYPED_NAME` case in `d_print_comp_inner`
+- In binutils 2.26, the loop reads: `while (local_name->type == DEMANGLE_COMPONENT_RESTRICT_THIS ...)` — dereferencing `local_name` without a NULL check
+- In binutils 2.40, the same loop reads: `while (typed_name != NULL && is_fnqual_component_type(typed_name->type))` — the `!= NULL` guard prevents the crash
+- Additionally, the `d_print_comp` wrapper in 2.40 adds an outer guard: `if (dc == NULL || dc->d_printing > 1 || dpi->recursion > MAX_RECURSION_COUNT)` — a second independent layer of protection
+- **Live PoC test:** The official crash input (`poc5` from `caozhzh/CRGF-Vul`) was run against binutils 2.40 compiled from Debian Bookworm source — result: **exit 0, no crash**
+- **No upstream fix commit exists** — fix was applied organically; no CVE-targeted patch was ever issued
+- All major distributions have deferred: Debian (unimportant), Ubuntu ("dos on very old version"), Red Hat (Bug #2425827, NEW, no fix version)
+
+---
+
+## ⚠️ Why You Don't Need to Fix It
+
+- **No vulnerable code present in 2.40** — the `while (local_name->type == ...)` crash path does not exist; replaced by `while (typed_name != NULL && ...)`
+- **PoC confirmed non-reproducible** on binutils 2.40 — official crash input exits cleanly with no SIGSEGV
+- **No security impact** on Debian bookworm systems
+- **False positive from scanners** — CVE NVD CPE only covers `gnu:binutils:2.26`; scanners flag by package name without code-level validation
+- Debian Security Tracker explicitly notes: *"most certainly bogus since assigned for a very old binutils release"*
+- Ubuntu Security notes: *"dos on very old version of binutils"*
+
+---
+
+## 🔗 References
+
+- [**NVD Entry – CVE-2025-66864**](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-66864)
+- [**Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2025-66864**](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2025-66864)
+- [**Ubuntu Security – CVE-2025-66864**](https://ubuntu.com/security/CVE-2025-66864)
+- [**Red Hat Bugzilla – Bug #2425827**](https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=2425827)
+- [**Official PoC – caozhzh/CRGF-Vul poc5**](https://github.com/caozhzh/CRGF-Vul/blob/main/cxxfilt/crash5.md)
+- [**Debian binutils 2.40 (bookworm)**](https://packages.debian.org/bookworm/binutils)
