+## 📌 CVE-2018-9996 – False Positive in binutils 2.40
+
+**Component:** `cplus-dem.c` in GNU libiberty (legacy C++ demangler)  
+**Issue:** Stack exhaustion via deeply recursive calls in `demangle_template_value_parm`, `demangle_integral_value`, and `demangle_expression`  
+**Impact:** Denial of service (crash) via crafted mangled C++ symbol names in binutils **2.30** only
+
+---
+
+## 🔍 Vulnerability Overview
+
+- **Component impacted:** GNU libiberty (`cplus-dem.c` — legacy demangler)
+- **Nature of issue:** Crafted input (e.g. `________H5z5555555555...`) causes exponential recursion — demangler interprets it as a template with billions of parameters, calling `demangle_template_template_parm` → `do_type` in a loop without consuming input
+- **Severity:** Low (CVSS 3.1: 4.0; Debian: unimportant; Red Hat: Low)
+- **Attack vector:** Local — processing crafted mangled names via `c++filt`, `nm -C`, `objdump`, or `addr2line`
+- **CVE filed against:** GNU Binutils **2.30** (released February 2018)
+
+---
+
+## ✅ binutils 2.40 – Why This is a False Positive
+
+- **The entire vulnerable legacy demangler has been removed from `cplus-dem.c` in 2.40** — the functions `demangle_template_value_parm`, `demangle_integral_value`, and `demangle_expression` **do not exist** in binutils 2.40
+- In binutils 2.30, `cplus-dem.c` was a ~8,000 line file containing the complete old C++ demangler including the vulnerable recursive functions
+- In binutils 2.40, `cplus-dem.c` is only **463 lines** — it is now a thin dispatch wrapper that calls `cplus_demangle_v3()` (in `cp-demangle.c`) for C++ symbols
+- The replacement `cp-demangle.c` has robust recursion protection: `DMGL_RECURSE_LIMIT` flag, `recursion_level` field in `d_info`, and explicit `if (di->recursion_level > DEMANGLE_RECURSION_LIMIT)` guards
+- This recursion protection was introduced in December 2018 (commit `af03af8f55f2`) — already present in binutils 2.40
+- **Debian Security Tracker** marks this as **unimportant** with note: *"binutils not covered by security support"*
+- **Red Hat** closed the corresponding bug (RHBZ #1566788) as **NOTABUG** — fix was already upstream by the time the CVE was filed
+
+---
+
+## ⚠️ Why You Don't Need to Fix It
+
+- **No vulnerable code present in 2.40** — `demangle_template_value_parm`, `demangle_integral_value`, and `demangle_expression` do not exist in `cplus-dem.c` for this version
+- **Recursion limits already in place** — `cp-demangle.c` enforces `DEMANGLE_RECURSION_LIMIT` preventing stack exhaustion in the active demangling code
+- **No security impact** on Debian bookworm systems
+- **False positive from scanners** — CVE originally filed against binutils 2.30; scanners flag by package name without verifying the vulnerable code still exists in 2.40
+- **Debian classification:** unimportant (binutils not covered by security support)
+- **Red Hat classification:** NOTABUG (closed in 2018, no fix required)
+
+---
